Triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, totaling 29 percent
A noticeable weakening of both parties of the previous grand coalition and a significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties brought after the first preliminary results the early parliamentary elections of Sunday in Austria.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly severe losses, where the position of previous chairman Wilhelm Molterer is seriously on the edge.
In contrast, the Electoral Director of the Alliance for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the Carinthian state captain Jörg Haider, is preparing for a triumphant return to federal politics.
According to the results so far, Social Democracy (SPÖ) remains the strongest force in the country with 29.8 percent of the votes, but it loses 5.5 percent of the votes compared to the last elections in 2006.
Even worse was the ÖVP, which loses almost nine percent of the votes with 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of these two major parties in Austria's post-war history, and especially with the People's Party, which demanded the early elections, this is a truly disastrous result.
At the beginning of July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the People's Party had a clear lead over the SPÖ.
The voters, however, probably punished the party for making the government fail.
Already in the first reactions to the results there were speculations about a possible resignation of the party chairman and previous Vice Chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could already be the case on Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party bureau.
Such a development would probably pave the way to the most likely way out of the electoral debacle, i.e. to renew the grand coalition of SPÖ and ÖVP.
In view of the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties - the Freedom Party (FPÖ) received 18 per cent for the time being, while the BZÖ received eleven per cent of the votes - the Social Democrats expressed their fear that 1999 could be repeated when the People's Party had reached agreement with the populists (at that time the FPÖ was still uniform, in 2005 it split from the BZÖ) with regard to a common government, which had even caused sanctions on the part of the European Union.
Jörg Haider, who has already stated that he is willing to cooperate with each party, is obviously relying on this development and expects to return to Vienna for Austrian federal policy.
The Green Party also entered the parliament, but it suffered slight losses and slipped from third to fifth among the Austrian political parties.
No other party has probably mastered the four per cent hurdle and therefore did not move into parliament.
