Organizers record increasing booking numbers
It seems to be a good winter for the German tour operators:
According to a study, sales for travel bookings for the coming months increased significantly compared to the previous year - even by more than 30 percent for the winter season.
Despite weak economic prospects, according to a study, the Germans' desire to travel remains unclouded.
In the bookings for the winter season, the rice offices recorded a turnover increase of 31 percent compared to the same period of the previous year, as the German Travel Association (DRV) reported in Berlin on Monday.
According to the investigation of the market research institute GfK, booking figures have also increased for the autumn months.
For example, the turnover increase of travel agencies for October was around 11 percent compared to 2007, according to the DRV.
The basis for these results are figures from the GfK, which evaluates monthly booking data from 1200 German travel agencies and extrapolates for the total market.
This includes travel bookings made until the end of August 2008.
Due to the weak dollar rate, travels to the USA in particular are in demand, the DRV reported.
Here the increase in the booking amounted to about one third.
In addition, Spain, Turkey and Greece, as well as the domestic areas of the Germans, are particularly sought after destinations.
In particular, travel packages would be very popular, explained DRV President Klaus Laepple.
In view of the rising costs for energy and food, the costs here are "better calculable for the customer than for individually organised holidays".
Money could save consumers, among other things, through early bird discounts or all-inclusive offers, Laepple explained.
The summer months were also very well booked, so that there will again be a turnover increase compared to the previous year - although, according to another study, the number of Germans who made a trip decreased compared to the previous year.
