`Auto bee' that avoids collisions
In order to advance the development of the technologies for accident prevention, Nissan was inspired this time by nature, more precisely by the bees.
The Japanese company has developed a robot whose flight goes back to the swarm behavior of bees and avoids accidents.
This robot is a Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C and represents the first step in the technologies for accident prevention.
The engineers from the technical development center of Nissan Motor Co. have developed this small robot in cooperation with Research Center for Advanced Science and Technology of the renowned University of Tokyo (Japan).
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Head of Technology PR and R&D Brand Management, the BR23C represents an extension of the four-layer Nissan safety shield.
This robot is supposed to ensure that the cars of this brand are able to avoid collisions.
During the flight, each bee builds up its own oval flight space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important are the bee's facet eyes, which can be seen in all directions over an angle of 300 degrees, allowing her to fly undisturbed in her personal airspace without interruption.
In order to recreate the all-round perspective, the technicians developed the so-called Laser Range Finder (LRF).
He notices obstacles that are up to two metres apart in front of the BR23C and are 180 degrees radius, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an in-vehicle microprocessor, which is directly translated into signal for avoiding collision
`At the moment when obstacle is noticed, the little robot will imitate the bee flight and immediately change direction by turning its wheels around 90o or even larger angles to avoid the collision.
The biggest difference to any other system is that this evasive maneuver is absolutely instinctive.
If it weren't, the robot might not be able to react with sufficient speed to avoid obstacles,' explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the senior engineer of this project.
In contrast to a bee, the robot cannot deviate upwards or downwards, nor can it be overtly; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to rotate its wheels and not in infinite directions and in infinite ways as the bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used the rotation function in addition to acceleration and braking functions, so that the small robot avoids collisions.
`This device only needs a few seconds to process the information and to act according to this information.
It does not require saving neither the information nor the intuitive logic of the maneuvers done, so it can work continuously with just a few more dozen KB of storage space.
That sounds surprising, but it's not about the GBs and not even the MBs of the disk space.
This is the first step in the development of technologies for the immediate prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan predicts to introduce in the next ten years at serial cars.
The robot works with lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than variety of lithium ion batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be the integration of the unit with a GPS navigation system by satellite, in order to lead to the goal while driving, avoiding the obstacles on the way.
