Morgan Stanley makes its capital available for MUFG
Morgan Stanley announced the entry of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG) into its company, making it the first bank in Japan to spend nine billion dollars and thus take over 21% of its capital, an innovation due to a strong fall in its stock market price.
One week after a preliminary agreement was made public, the two banks declared that MUFG will buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley common shares at a uniform price of $25.25, which amounts to a total of $3 billion.
The assumed price is less than 19% of the share price of August 31st.
MUFG will invest an additional six billion dollars in the acquisition of convertible shares that will secure a 10% profit and can be resold at a price of 31.25 dollars.
Morgan Stanley stated that the global business will be conducted on the basis of a uniform average price of $29, which is 28% above the current price.
The Morgan Stanley share, however, declined by 6.79% to 23.07 dollars at 17.00 GMT.
"This strategic link is an important opportunity to accelerate the transition from Morgan Stanley to holding bank status," said John Mack, Director General of the American Group.
Morgan Stanley assumed this status last week, which is supposed to allow him to expand his business to new areas, but under the supervision of the Federal Reserve.
Their connection with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis forces the biggest names of Wall Street to take a much more cautious stance than before.
The modalities presented on Monday also show that the agreement was changed over the last few days: last Monday Morgan simply declared that she would sell up to 20% of her shares to Japan for about $8.5 billion.
'A week ago', Toshihide Mizuno, Managing Director of MUFG, said in Tokyo, 'we thought that the stake would be made up entirely of common shares.
But in view of the current economic and market situation, we wanted to reduce risks and secure ourselves.'
Based on a balanced average price, MUFG will pay 7% below its market value for its Morgan Stanley shares.
And the business will go with a reduction in profit of about 20% per share.
The agreement provides that in one year, MUFG will be able to convert half of its preference shares into common shares if the latter are exchanged more than 50% above the sales value within a given period, i.e. approximately 47 dollars.
Morgan Stanley assures that the funds supplied by MUFG will allow him to exploit investment opportunities, strengthen their balance sheet and increase their sales.
However, a press spokesman of the group refused to provide more detailed information on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
After the investment of MUFG, Morgan Stanley should be able to book a solvency ratio of about 15%, one of the best in this sector.
Morgan explained that since the end of August his balance sheet has been 'clearly' lowered.
The last few weeks have been hard for the group that had to watch their stock market price fall by half, while the price of insurance against insolvency has skyrocketed.
This price declined on Monday, but remained at a high level, at about 12%.
Goldman Sachs, the only other 'survivors' of the big investment banks on Wall Street after the bankruptcy of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the purchase of Merrill Lynch, announced last week that they had withdrawn 15 billion dollars, in part from Berkshire Hathaway, the Warren Buffett group.
Rafael Correa this Monday in Quito.
Refounding the Republic around the socialism of the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Equatorialian Rafael Correa.
It was that third person who, following the example of his like-minded and friends, put the plan of a new constitution for election this Sunday.
Mission accomplished, because according to the public results, which amounted to 80% of the vote, 64% voted 'yes' in the referendum.
According to these results, 28% voted 'No', 7% of the ballots were invalid and 0.7% were delivered empty.
For the constitutional project to be adopted, more than half of all votes cast must be cast.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the polling stations' exits and a census of a non-governmental organisation announced a clear victory for 'yes', and 63% to 70% predicted it.
In the night from Sunday to Monday Rafael Correa had demanded the victory of his constitutional project.
The 'constitution has triumphed in an overwhelming way', he had assured in Guayaquil, the seat of the government 280 kilometers southwest of Quito, and congratulated the Equatorians.
Of course Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales, but also by his Chilean like-minded Michelle Bachelet.
The election, which was held silently in accordance with the observation order of the Organization of American States (OAS), referred to a text consisting of 444 points in order to secure 'new socialism' for which the President is committed.
The constitutional project transfers state power to the economy by giving it the sole right to 'development planning' in a country that lives largely from oil production by foreign companies and from foreign currencies that send emigrants to the country.
The plan, promoted by the Correa elected in 2006, also grants the head of state greater power, which will be able to exercise up to two consecutive mandates of four years each, and will have the possibility of disbanding the National Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and aspire to a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution also guarantees the principle of free medical care and education, which the President has already begun to introduce in this country with 13.9 million inhabitants, in which 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
In the end, it also intends to ban the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington to use an Equatorian base as a base for American anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages were released in Chad
An Egyptian command started the attack on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions who had been captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions, who were held in the desert for eleven days, were brought back to the Egyptian capital healthy and intact this Monday afternoon.
In the morning they were liberated from an Egyptian command in Chad.
Apparently in good condition, the hostages reached the Al-Maza military base right next to Cairo International Airport at around 3.30 p.m. on board a special aircraft.
They were taken directly, without being able to talk to the press, on board a helicopter to the Maadi Hospital, a foreigners' district of Cairo, to be examined there.
They all enjoy 'best health' and 'no ransom was paid to the kidnappers', explained the Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna on the runway.
After being captured on 19 September in an off-road safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat in the border area of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, the group of hostages was repeatedly taken from one hideout to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
There are eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and also eight Egyptians: two leaders, four chauffeurs, a border guard and the director of the agency Egyptus, organizer of the safari.
An Egyptian security officer stated that 30 members of the Special Forces, from on board two helicopters, launched the attack at night just before dawn.
"On both sides, shots were fired and half of the kidnappers were killed, the rest fled," said this person in charge who wants to remain anonymous.
He stated that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian Special Forces had been sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
The head of the Italian diplomat Franco Frattini reported from Belgrade, where he is now, on the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian Special Forces.
'We must acknowledge that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our men from the intelligence and the special units', he explained without further details.
He also denied that a ransom had been paid.
The evening before, the Sudanese army claimed to have stopped an off-road vehicle in a patrol that contained the hijackers, killing six of them, including the leader from Chad, and two arrests.
The army declared that they were in contact with a rebel group from Darfur, the Libération du Soudan-Unité (SLA-U), which immediately denied this movement.
Letters - The silent majority of culture
A debate on the financing of culture makes headlines and is central to the current election campaign.
All the better.
But one area of our cultural life remains forgotten.
Who will stand up and denounce the pitiful sums given to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historical sites that starve miserably?
Which politician will dare to remind the Federal Government that it is neglecting its monuments and its culturally important buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, there are no real laws that effectively protect our cultural heritage?
Did you know that the French government is making 3.5 million euros available solely for the restoration of the Château de Chinon in the Loire Valley?
Our American neighbours are told in their country's constitution that the protection of cultural heritage is part of the American culture, and that this cultural heritage must be protected by all citizens, all MPs and all government districts, in mutual consultation.
In Quebec, in the Association of the History Societies of Quebec, at least 40,000 volunteers gathered in 211 historical societies are trying to deal intensively with history, save the numerous private archives with a few penny, and preserve the archaeological remains.
They are also often the watchdogs of our cultural heritage who protest with the power of despair when supporters and decision makers release their bulldozers on our old stones and forgotten cemeteries.
When will there be a stage for history and cultural heritage?
Benelux governments nationalize parts of Fortis Bank
With a partial nationalisation, the Benelux countries want to help the Belgian-Dutch Fortis Bank, which is in turmoil as a result of the US financial crisis: the three countries provide a total of EUR 11.2 billion to the banking and insurance institute, which also has branches in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands consulted at the highest level on the weekend, together with the President of the European Central Bank and the Commissioner for Competition of the European Commission.
In the eurozone, the Fortis is the first victim of the international financial market crisis that has been going on for a year, so decisions that are now being taken in connection with the Bank could have a precedent.
In accordance with the decision taken on Sunday night, all three states buy the respective shares of the bank to about 49 percent.
The bank will probably sell part of its holdings, especially the insurance activities purchased last year by the Dutch ABN Amro.
The shares of the Fortis started a steep decline last week, and serious crisis scenarios were already emerging in the second half of the week.
However, analysts agree that the bank, with its 85,000 employees, is far too large for bankruptcy.
The institution's securities fell by 12% to a 14-year low on Friday.
Since January, the value of the shares has fallen by more than two thirds.
In view of the current share prices, the market value of the Group is EUR 14 billion, which is unrealistic according to the management.
In the management's view, the USD 700 billion US bailout package and the resulting uncertainty in the markets are to blame for the decline in Fortis shares.
On Monday, however, the courses rose slightly.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed new Director-General of the Bank.
The financial institution was also looking for a private buyer, but there was no interested party with an objective offer.
However, the Belgian government was trying to calm down - no investor should tremble for his money, it said.
There has been no panic among customers, the bank's branches have not been stormed.
In Hungary, the Fortis has independent branches, but it also names leasing companies as its own.
Fox in the henhouse
Because of a person’s drug use, life and health insurance companies in America often refuse to sign a contract with a customer.
Data protection experts fear that the data market could become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programs that link the use of the drug data to the consent of the data subject in any case.
These should be in independent hands, otherwise we entrust the fox to the chickens" - quotes the Washington Post Richard Dick, developer of the program for tracking prescription data.
Insurance companies set the fees and the payment amounts in case of damage depending on the customer's health and if the risk is overestimated, the insurance is not even completed.
In the past, the customer was sent to a medical examination and the contract was concluded only with knowledge of the results of the examination.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper method: using the customer's identification number, he obtains the data of the last one and a half years from the pharmacies, i.e., which preparations were purchased, and the program calculates from it which disease the customer suffers from and how his health is.
For example, if he regularly buys large amounts of cholesterol-lowering medication, it could be concluded that his blood fat level is untreatable, which would automatically put him in a higher risk group.
There are several versions of the program in circulation - some even define a risk multiplier, so insurance companies only have to deal with the paperwork, but there are minor difficulties.
One of the drawbacks is that many medicines can be taken for various purposes, such as migraines and hot flushes, but also depression.
The latter is a high risk factor from the insurer's point of view, while the above mentioned does not.
For the retrieval and processing of the data, own societies have formed which, before obtaining the data, ask the patient for his consent.
In the meantime, they have to do so by law, although omissions have not yet been punished.
Some companies even process the results of laboratory tests and combine them with the data on drug use, thus providing an even more accurate picture of the patient's health.
More and more companies have access to the data and control of their use is becoming more difficult at the same time.
Although there is a separate data protection law for health data, its impact only extends to health service providers and insurance companies.
The bill has already been submitted to Congress, according to which the authorities could also control the data processing companies.
Dick Richard realizes that this is too little, so he wants to develop his program further, so that the data can only be passed on with the consent of the person concerned.
Another question, of course, is that the person concerned can hardly prohibit access to his data, since the insurance companies do not otherwise conclude a contract with him.
And so the chickens are in some way left to the fox's mercy.
Global menu from Marseille
European Union and India double trade
Since the European Union and India are both leading trading partners of each other, this was the main topic, along with other global problems, at the ninth summit.
Today, the French-Indian summit is also taking place, which is mainly about cooperation in the nuclear energy sector.
While the European Union recognises that India is an emerging, democratic great power that should be given more voice and say when it comes to international concerns, member states have not yet been able to agree whether or not to support the permanent membership of New Delhi in the UN Security Council.
This question was not even discussed at yesterday's ninth summit in Marseilles yesterday.
The French President and current EU President Nicolas Sarkozy, as well as Commission President José Manuel Barroso and Chief Diplomate Javier Solana received Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh. An agreement was reached to double trade over the next five years, i.e. increase to a good EUR 100 billion.
In view of the fact that the exchange of goods had increased from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this target is not even so ambitious.
In this sense, the 26 existing civil aviation agreements with India have also been legally merged into an agreement, so that air transport will also be boosted in the future.
India wants to sign the free trade agreement with the Union by 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the pact.
The aim is to strike a balance in the currently unbalanced relationship between the EU and India: while the Union is India's number one partner, New Delhi is only 9th among the EU partners.
The summit was dedicated to global concerns.
Among them was the situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan, or terrorism, which both sides strongly condemned, and the convening of a UN conference was also urgised.
The Doha Round should also be completed, with both sides to blame for its failure.
The EU stressed that it is sticking to its energy and climate programme, i.e. that pollutant emissions should be reduced by at least 20% by 2020.
India also agreed with this, as did the proposal to make a kind of global compromise at the next climate summit and to reduce greenhouse gas production by 50 percent by 2050.
Food prices should also be combated, so both support the call for an international conference on the subject of financial crisis.
The Indian head of government is today visiting the French capital, where he will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy at a bilateral meeting.
In Paris, however, it is hoped that orders will be made to French companies worth EUR 20 billion for the construction of nuclear reactors in India.
According to the Agency's reports, the agreement is to be concluded for 15 years.
More than 300 Italian publishers in Frankfurt
Strong presence of Italian publishers at the International Frankfurt Book Fair.
More than 300 Italian publishers will be present at the 60th Book Fair, the most important international event for the acquisition of rights.
The international Frankfurt Book Fair is expecting more than 7,000 exhibitors from 101 countries for the current event. They will spread over the 171.790 square meters of the fair and present over 403,000 titles. Turkey will be the guest of honour of the event.
The Undersecretary for the Ministry of Cultural Heritage and Activities Maria Giro will represent the Italian Government in the exhibition hall during the opening ceremony: Italy will represent the 264 m2 exhibition space "Punto Italia".
This will be followed by a press conference near the Room structure in the exhibition hall 5.0 of the Book Fair: on this occasion, figures, trends and perspectives around the publishing industry in Italy will be discussed.
According to the data, the importance of the books of foreign writers decreases throughout, but especially in the adult and youth sectors.
Found the billionaire Steve Fossett's small plane that disappeared a year ago
The small aircraft of Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared on a flight over the Nevada desert on September 3, 2007 was found.
The items have been found on a high plateau of 3000 m altitude, in the area of Sierra Nevada Mammoth Lakes between the states of California and Nevada.
However, no human remains were found inside the aircraft.
The Sheriff of Madera County, John Anderson, completely dispelled the last doubts during a press conference: "The plane has been located, and a troop has been sent to do so. Now we have the certainty that it is the plane with which Steve Fossett flew on the day of his disappearance."
Mr. Anderson also confirmed that no human remains were found on the plane or near it.
The 63-year-old billionaire was declared dead in February.
The U.S. Department of Road Safety (Ntsb) noted that a crew was sent out just a few hours after the sighting of the aircraft, which identified the aircraft: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, which was lost on September 3, 2007, after Fossett had taken off on a 3-hour flight in Yerington, Nevada.
Yesterday, in California, near the Nevada border, some of Fossett's personal belongings were found by a couple near their home at Mammoth Lakes.
These are two passports with the name Fossetts, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a jacket.
The search for Fossett had been abandoned a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had won a place in history through a long succession of records.
In 2002, he was the first person to circle the world ball in a hot air balloon in his sixth attempt: a two-week, lonely flight.
Three years later, he flew around the world in a single flight without a stopover by plane.
Among his numerous records is also a flight of 15445 m above the Andes, this one with a co-pilot.
Glk, the advertising you don't expect
A Suv that falls out of the traditional patterns due to its original design and special lines, the extending surface and its clear angles.
With this offroader, Mercedes-Benz has tried to breathe new breath into the sector.
Due to its exceptional characteristics, the presentation of the Suv Glk will also be unconventional, which will be on display in the Mercedes-Benz showroom from 17 October.
Thus, the advertising drum that will accompany the appearance of the new model will also appear in a new dress, namely in the form of a 3D campaign – a novelty in the automotive sector in the backward Italy.
A project with a maximum effort, which will be carried out in various fibers, which will occupy the central shopping street of Milan, the Corso Como, by 15 November.
The first façade will consist of the presentation of the car in form, whereby 3D glasses distributed near the Corso Como will give the whole a special look: the new Suv will appear in its almost real dimensions as a three-dimensional model.
In fact, the car will appear to emerge from the poster on which it is depicted.
With the help of the Elumina8 technology, the new Glk is illuminated in all its details in different moments, in order to put itself together again as a whole.
Without a doubt, the aim of Mercedes with this advertisement is to introduce a new kind of autoreclamation into this rather stereotyped field.
But will it be possible to attract the interest of future buyers? We will see it.
Now it is clear who the Italian hooligans are
They're from Triveneto – now they're risking stadium ban
Who are these 150-200 boys and girls, for whom all of Italy is ashamed? They are part of the group "Ultras Italia", which has been traveling after the Italian national team for years and which, frankly, did not cause any serious problems until recently.
Never before has there been clashes with opposing fans.
The origin of the group lies in the right milieu.
The sponsors come from the Triveneto.
From Verona, Padova, Trieste and Udine.
Other smaller groups from Campania and Apulia joined them in Sofia.
They carry the Tricolori, on which the cities of militants appear: however, they were removed on Saturday to avoid identification.
Their role models are the English fans.
In Bulgaria there was now a clash with a truly radical right-wing fan scene, that of Levski.
The Figc had provided the Italian fans with 144 cards for the game: all were issued in names and thus easy to control.
In fact, they were all controlled by the Viminal: among those who travelled to Sofia, there was no one with an ongoing stadium ban procedure.
Four fans of the Italian team, who were already preloaded in this respect, were denied the ticket and the trip to Bulgaria.
Now the Viminal is waiting for the reports of the Bulgarian police to take further steps: in this case, the arrested or identified Tifosi can expect a stadium ban of at least five years.
This is an international ban which prevents access to stadiums throughout Europe.
So our hooligans won't put a foot in a stadium anymore.
Thank God.
But now, of course, there is fear of imitation offenders, who could follow these little more than 150.
"This fire must be withdrawn immediately, and this does not in any case give such behaviour the opportunity to justify it," says the Viminal.
Therefore, "eyes to especially also with a view to the match of the national team on Wednesday in Lecce."
Indeed, there is a small nucleus of the Italian ultras in Puglia.
Tomorrow the Osservatorio (Sports Supervision) gathers, on Tuesday the Casms, which can count on part of the Aise, i.e. the secret services dealing with the problem of stadium violence.
"Duce-Duce calls and the raised right arm during the anthem of Mameli? In Bulgaria this is not a crime..."
This is the thought of Domenico Mazzilli (clearly expressed in no joy), who has been the director of the Osservatorio on the Viminal for a few weeks (he took over the post of Frenchsco Tagliente and then Felice Ferlizzi).
Previously, Mazzilli was the police president of Trieste, where a core of supporters of Ultras Italia, founded in 2002, now comes from.
It is true, says Mazzilli, that in Bulgaria it is not against the law to praise the Duce, but without a doubt the behaviour of these 150-200 people was a disgrace.
"I am not a sociologist – adds No. 1 of the Osservatorio – crimes are punished in the country of their deed.
So far, this group had been in check, but now it has to be reconsidered what has happened and what will happen.
But let us also speak of the whistles during the anthem Mamelis: even though this is not a crime, but allow me, there is no education...".
